h intellectual collaboration. Philosophers have long been familiar with Descartes’s side of the correspondence. Now Elisabeth’s letters—never before available in translation in their entirety—emerge this volume, adding much-needed context and depth both to Descartes’s ideas and the legacy of the princess. Lisa Shapiro’s annotated edition—which also includes Elisabeth’s correspondence with the Quakers William Penn and Robert Barclay—will be heralded by students of philosophy, feminist theorists, and historians of the early modern period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPhilosophy, Modernx17th century. 0aPhilosophy, Moderny17th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aDescartes, René, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKing, Margaret L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabil, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShapiro, Lisa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226204444423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226204444.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles